# The Book of Instruments

A book about **the things that make the sound**. Not a book about how
to compose — that is Music. Not a book about how motion feels — that
is Motion. This book is about the specific voices of the specific
instruments the runtime can call on, and how each one is played.

Music teaches the *musical mind* — melody, harmony, polyrhythm — in
a way that transfers across any instrument. This book teaches the
opposite: the concrete, per-instrument knowledge that Music
deliberately does not carry. Which instruments exist. How each one
is made to sound (its synthesis profile, its voice). How each one
is played (its articulations, its ranges, its idiomatic use).

*When Music says \"play a C4,\" it does not say on what. A C4 on a
piano and a C4 on a shakuhachi are the same pitch and completely
different worlds. The piano's C4 is a hammer on a string with a
hard onset and a decay. The shakuhachi's C4 is a breath through a
bamboo tube with a slow onset and a wobble. Music is the note.
Instruments is the mouth the note comes out of.*

Every fenced program in this book is a full runnable program. Every
one calls `synth/*` or `play/*` verbs against the sealed sound
engine. If you paste any block into `motoi-scheme repl` with audio
enabled, it plays. That is what \"living tutorial\" means for this
book: the instrument you read about is the instrument that speaks.

## The first five chapters

1. [[#chapter-1]] **The roster.** The instruments the runtime can voice.
   The families they belong to, the license-clear synthesis profiles
   they draw from, how to ask what is available.
2. [[#chapter-2]] **Piano.** The instrument most readers already
   know. Synthesis, articulation, and how it is played — from a
   single note to a full pedaled chord.
3. [[#chapter-3]] **Strings.** Bowed strings, plucked strings. Bow
   pressure, portamento, ensemble. The section as a voice.
4. [[#chapter-4]] **Percussion.** Attack, decay, tuned versus
   untuned. Kits, single hits, and rolls.
5. [[#chapter-5]] **The Japanese bamboo flute.** Shakuhachi. Breath
   as note. Silence as a note. The instrument whose absence is
   half the sound.

## What this book is not

- Not the Book of Music. Music teaches ideas about sound in time.
  Instruments teaches which specific voice is producing that sound.
  Don't fold instrument-specific knowledge back into Music.
- Not the Book of Sound. Sound teaches the engineering of a sound —
  waveforms, envelopes, filters, FFTs. This book uses the results of
  Sound to make each instrument sing. When Sound teaches you *how*
  a filter shapes an oboe reed, this book uses that filter to give
  the oboe its voice.
- Not a MIDI reference. There are no bank numbers here. There is a
  roster of named instruments, each with a voice you can hear.

## The verbs this book uses

The general primitives, in the order they appear:

- `synth/select` — pick which instrument voice is active.
- `synth/available?` — check whether an instrument is on the roster.
- `synth/roster` — list every instrument on the roster.
- `synth/profile` — read the synthesis profile of a named
  instrument.
- `play/note` — play a note on the current instrument.
- `play/chord` — play multiple notes together.
- `play/articulation!` — set the articulation (legato, staccato,
  pizzicato, etc.).
- `play/dynamics!` — set the loudness (pp through ff).
- `synth/pedal!` — sustain pedal on or off.
- `synth/bow!` — bow control on strings.
- `synth/breath!` — breath control on winds.
- `synth/damp!` — dampen a note or a whole voice.

Everything else is a combination.

## How to read it

- Read the fenced program.
- Predict what the instrument will sound like.
- Run it in the REPL with audio enabled.
- Change one number.
- Run it again and hear what changed.

Predicting the sound before you run it is the exercise. Hearing
whether you were right is the check.

> **Warning**
>
> None of the programs here are safe to skip. Every one is a
> training pair. If you skim, you skim past the point.

> **Tip**
>
> Read this book with headphones on. Many of the differences between
> instrument voices — the exact color of a bow's attack, the way a
> shakuhachi's breath colors its onset — are wiped out by laptop
> speakers.

## Persisting instrument state

When you save an instrument setup — a piano voicing, a bowed-string
articulation, a shakuhachi breath preset — the state serializes as an
`artifact-state` SLAT record on disk. Same shape as any other
artifact. If you want to see the format, [[book-of-slat]] Chapter 5
and Appendix C both include an `artifact-state` example.

